<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission from Mrs</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence Submitted by Mrs. A. Underwood.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is to alert the Committee to the way that the Department of Education appears to be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">-using Clause C of the new Growth and Infrastructure Law to impose the Free Schools where they are not needed on Greenbelt land which is deemed unsuitable for purpose by the District Planning Committee.   In particular, this is evident with reference to Pioneer House in Stoke </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Poges</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, South Bucks.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Pioneer House is a Greenbelt site which has legal restraints on it for no further development.   It also has restrictions for noise levels and no more </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 175 employees.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DfE’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> planning application to change its use to a secondary Free School would mean around 1000 pupils and staff arriving and leaving each day.  The site is surrounded by residential houses, narrow lanes with few pavements and no street lighting.  There is no direct public transport to this site.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Planning was due to be refused on six different grounds including by the Highways Agency.   On learning this, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> withdrew their application the day before and went ahead to buy the site at truly excessive cost quoting Clause C of the Act (which then had not been finalised).   They did this despite written assurances from several </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> persons, including Lord Nash, that they would NOT pre-empt the planning decision.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Khalsa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Academy did not consult with the local community in any way before we were aware of the school’s apparent new site.     The first year had already been filled with, I believe, 92% Sikh children, in spite of a requirement to be 50/50 non-Sikh.   Because as a village we protested (peacefully) against any secondary school on this site, we now have received Solicitor’s threatening letters on behalf of this Academy.   I believe there is not a single child who will walk to this school.   The whole situation is in no way compatible with the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DfE’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> stated reason for Free Schools:  “set up in response to what local people say they want and need in order to improve education for children in their community”.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Khalsa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Free School/Academy may become an excellent school but it is placed in the wrong site.   Nearly all the pupils will come from Slough (Berkshire) and the West of London whereas South Bucks has already enough secondary places.   Slough in Berkshire even has an empty school it has refused to release.   Currently only 5 pupils come from anywhere in Buckinghamshire.  Pioneer House is totally unsuitable on so many different grounds for any secondary school and our Greenbelt heritage should be protected.    The blatant waste of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">taxpayers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> money by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and their disregard for the unsuitability of the site is incomprehensible.   The evidence of transport and noise impact, the strong possibility of  contamination on the site and the local opposition is irrefutable.   The promised “localism” should be heard.   It is tantamount to a dictatorship that local planning committees are wilfully disregarded and Clause C is used to ride roughshod over the legitimate protests of a local community.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We have now heard that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are using Clause K of the new Law in total contempt of our local planning committee and any common sense.  How can Permitted Development Rights be an option when the application was already on the point of being refused?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are a village of around 5,000 with many Asian residents and we have always integrated happily.   Faith schools seem to divide instead of uniting communities and I fear for the future of the UK if more faith schools are encouraged.   The local Sikhs in our village oppose this or any secondary school here and it is said they have received intimidation and abuse for their stance.    I have read that there are threats and racial name-calling on social networks against our village campaigners.   I have heard of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Khalsa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> schoolchildren calling over a fence to a resident in his garden “white man, go back inside”.    This is hardly acceptable behaviour and does nothing for social cohesion.   Please consider the potential future problems for our children, theirs and the generations to come.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>